## Conceptual Questions:
1. Symlinks vs. Hard Links
A hard link is a direct entry in a directory pointing to an inode, effectively becoming another name for the file; the OS forbids hard-linking directories to prevent permanent structural cycles. A symbolic link is just a text file containing a path to another file or directory. Because symlinks can point to ancestor directories, they can easily create infinite loops during traversal unless specifically detected.

2. Cycle Detection
Checking both st_dev and st_ino is necessary because inode numbers are only unique within a single filesystem. If you only check st_ino, you might incorrectly detect a "cycle" if two different files on two different mounted drives happen to share the same inode number.

3. Filesystem Boundaries
Detection works by comparing the st_dev field of a directory's metadata against the st_dev of the starting search path. When crossing a mount point (like moving from / to /proc), the st_dev ID changes because it represents the specific physical or virtual device where the data lives.

4. The VFS Layer
The Virtual File System (VFS) acts as an abstraction layer that provides a common set of system calls (like open, read, stat) for all filesystems. It translates these generic calls into the specific commands needed by individual drivers (like ext4 or NTFS), allowing user programs to interact with a unified directory tree without needing to know the technical details of the underlying hardware or storage format.

## Test and Run: 
```bash
make

python3 test_bfind_basic.py

# Our BFS find
./bfind my_test -name "*.c"

# System DFS find
find my_test -name "*.c"

# The -xdev test
./bfind / -xdev

# symlink loop test
./bfind -L my_test

# memeory leak test
valgrind --leak-check=full ./bfind my_test
leaks --atExit -- ./bfind my_test 



